<div id="review_3664829746" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3664829746" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9854096-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338281443p2/9854096.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3664829746?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/9854096-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780752883540" href="/book/show/4609638-hide-and-seek">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3664829746" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1121306020247244710">This is my third Ian Rankin book It&apos;s also the second in his Rebus series for which he&apos;s most famous for.<br/><br/> Like the first novel, Knots and Crosses, the main focus is the crime itself. From what I&apos;ve heard the author say in interviews this is the case for the first few novels until he fully hit his stride. However, this also allowed me to be pleasantly surprised that there was any character development at all.<br/><br/> This time around Rebus felt much more assertive and less melancholy than his first outin</span>
  <span id="freeText1121306020247244710" style="display:none">This is my third Ian Rankin book It's also the second in his Rebus series for which he's most famous for.<br /><br /> Like the first novel, Knots and Crosses, the main focus is the crime itself. From what I've heard the author say in interviews this is the case for the first few novels until he fully hit his stride. However, this also allowed me to be pleasantly surprised that there was any character development at all.<br /><br /> This time around Rebus felt much more assertive and less melancholy than his first outing. He's still not Mr Sunshine, but it's not like that's ever going to be the case, but he does come across as more confident and capable of his job. It's also a refreshing change to see someone in his position not be a complete dogsbody, unlike one other character by a favourite author, although his "old school" way of treating his sidekick was a bit much.<br /><br /> The case itself was pretty thin on the ground. There wasn't actually much of a case to start with but given Rebus' inability to let something go threads were snatched upon and half leads were followed. Rankin also wanted to emphasise that, just like Knots and Crosses, the book was using Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde as a template. But where the former gave subtle hints at this Hide and Seek made it so blatantly obvious that it might as well have flashed in bold letters in front of Rebus' face which I wasn't a fan of.<br /><br /> The ending wasn't great. The mystery was solved but, although realistic, I would have liked the outcome to be more satisfactory and conclusive.<br /><br /> So really it's a case of swings and roundabouts. The character development felt better than book 1 but the case itself wasn't much to write home about. Not that I wasn't kept guessing and not that I worked out who or what was behind everything but there wasn't much to go on and in another book you could imagine it not being investigated at all.<br /><br />All this adds up to another 3 star read. I've come to the realisation that the series will be a slow burner as Rankin continues to find out himself who Rebus is as a character and I'm fine with that. As long as they continue to improve and don't regress I'm more than happy to continue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1121306020247244710" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

